1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,075
There are two types or styles of assessing your data, visual and programmatic.

2
00:00:05,075 --> 00:00:08,370
Visual assessment is just opening your data and looking through it in

3
00:00:08,370 --> 00:00:11,955
its entirety in Jupyter Notebook or via pandas,

4
00:00:11,955 --> 00:00:15,835
a text editor, or a spreadsheet application, for example.

5
00:00:15,835 --> 00:00:18,540
Programmatic assessment, like its name suggests,

6
00:00:18,540 --> 00:00:21,120
uses code to view specific parts of the data,

7
00:00:21,120 --> 00:00:24,135
like using functions or methods to summarize the data.

8
00:00:24,135 --> 00:00:26,415
Like the df.info method, for example.

9
00:00:26,415 --> 00:00:28,245
You can even plot the data.

10
00:00:28,245 --> 00:00:31,265
When we assess data both visually and programmatically,

11
00:00:31,265 --> 00:00:35,150
we'll get into the habit of identifying and documenting issues.

12
00:00:35,150 --> 00:00:39,040
We can revisit whatever issues we found at the end of our assessment.

13
00:00:39,040 --> 00:00:44,330
There are two primary types of visual assessment, directed visual assessment,

14
00:00:44,330 --> 00:00:47,210
which involves systematically looking through each DataTable in

15
00:00:47,210 --> 00:00:51,580
a Jupyter Notebook or spreadsheet application like Google Sheets or MS Excel.

16
00:00:51,580 --> 00:00:55,625
Direct visual assessment can help detect issues such as missing values,

17
00:00:55,625 --> 00:00:58,405
outliers, or inconsistencies in the data.

18
00:00:58,405 --> 00:01:00,710
Suppose you are given a dataset in

19
00:01:00,710 --> 00:01:04,205
a spreadsheet containing students test scores, names, and ages.

20
00:01:04,205 --> 00:01:07,135
You can directly observe the data in the spreadsheet.

21
00:01:07,135 --> 00:01:10,580
You may spot a student's age as 120,

22
00:01:10,580 --> 00:01:13,235
which is likely an error that needs correcting.

23
00:01:13,235 --> 00:01:15,815
In this case, you're directly looking at the raw data

24
00:01:15,815 --> 00:01:18,740
and identifying potential issues or patterns.

25
00:01:18,740 --> 00:01:21,710
Unfortunately, some datasets are so large that

26
00:01:21,710 --> 00:01:24,470
spreadsheet programs will crash when trying to open them.

27
00:01:24,470 --> 00:01:28,055
Sometimes you may need to truncate the data for viewing purposes,

28
00:01:28,055 --> 00:01:31,120
for example, only view the first few rows.

29
00:01:31,120 --> 00:01:35,705
Non-directed visual assessment is when you look at different portions of tables closely,

30
00:01:35,705 --> 00:01:39,425
such as scrolling through the data in search of intriguing and relevant issues.

31
00:01:39,425 --> 00:01:41,180
Upon spawning something noteworthy,

32
00:01:41,180 --> 00:01:45,805
you can then narrow your focus to investigate that particular aspect in greater detail.

33
00:01:45,805 --> 00:01:47,445
Take the previous example.

34
00:01:47,445 --> 00:01:49,820
You begin scrolling through the student's data casually,

35
00:01:49,820 --> 00:01:52,820
observing any patterns or anomalies that catch your eye.

36
00:01:52,820 --> 00:01:55,340
While scrolling, you noticed several instances where

37
00:01:55,340 --> 00:01:58,615
students have the same name and age but different test scores.

38
00:01:58,615 --> 00:02:00,170
Intrigued by this auditing,

39
00:02:00,170 --> 00:02:02,990
you decide to investigate further to determine whether these are

40
00:02:02,990 --> 00:02:05,995
genuine cases of students with the same name and age,

41
00:02:05,995 --> 00:02:09,480
or if there are data quality issues such as duplicate entries,

42
00:02:09,480 --> 00:02:11,870
or inaccuracy that need to be addressed.

43
00:02:11,870 --> 00:02:15,730
In this case, you are now focusing on particular issues or errors.

44
00:02:15,730 --> 00:02:19,535
Let's take a look at a dataset example with the data of students names,

45
00:02:19,535 --> 00:02:22,715
ages, and scores on a test that I'm calling testing.

46
00:02:22,715 --> 00:02:25,390
Let's do some simple visual assessments.

47
00:02:25,390 --> 00:02:27,215
After reading the CSV file,

48
00:02:27,215 --> 00:02:32,510
I use the dot head function with the value 10 to show the first 10 rows of the DataFrame.

49
00:02:32,510 --> 00:02:34,310
Truncating my view of the dataframe,

50
00:02:34,310 --> 00:02:37,360
so I don't display 200 rows all at once.

51
00:02:37,360 --> 00:02:39,770
Now let's take a look at the DataFrame starting with

52
00:02:39,770 --> 00:02:42,415
direct visual assessment with the name column.

53
00:02:42,415 --> 00:02:46,970
One of the first things that we can notice is this question mark character in Roway for

54
00:02:46,970 --> 00:02:50,270
Liem Gibson's name that was most likely caused by an issue with

55
00:02:50,270 --> 00:02:53,990
an accent character not being supported by the encoding format.

56
00:02:53,990 --> 00:02:56,080
This is an accuracy issue.

57
00:02:56,080 --> 00:03:00,620
We also see the case of a student's age in Row 7 being 120,

58
00:03:00,620 --> 00:03:04,490
which is inaccurate and most likely due to a data entry error.

59
00:03:04,490 --> 00:03:09,620
Let's now take a look at the Test A score column showing students scores on Test A.

60
00:03:09,620 --> 00:03:14,645
Note how each data point is documented as numbers followed by an apostrophe.

61
00:03:14,645 --> 00:03:18,890
This means that pandas will interpret this data as a string rather than a number,

62
00:03:18,890 --> 00:03:22,210
which means we won't be able to use this data for calculations.

63
00:03:22,210 --> 00:03:24,710
This is a validity issue and is likely due to

64
00:03:24,710 --> 00:03:27,695
poor planning by whoever is recording this information.

65
00:03:27,695 --> 00:03:30,815
Let me direct you to another issue in Row 6.

66
00:03:30,815 --> 00:03:34,880
Note how the numbers for the age and test score columns are not numerical,

67
00:03:34,880 --> 00:03:36,440
but are instead strings.

68
00:03:36,440 --> 00:03:38,960
Whereas all of the other numbers in these columns are written

69
00:03:38,960 --> 00:03:41,995
with integer digits like 14 and 95.

70
00:03:41,995 --> 00:03:43,950
This is a consistency issue.

71
00:03:43,950 --> 00:03:46,160
This will be a big problem downstream,

72
00:03:46,160 --> 00:03:48,470
since the Row 7 may not be considered when we get

73
00:03:48,470 --> 00:03:51,535
summary statistics like the average age of the test taker.

74
00:03:51,535 --> 00:03:55,305
We can find another issue using non-directed visual assessment.

75
00:03:55,305 --> 00:03:59,455
The missing NaN values showing us that our data is not complete.

76
00:03:59,455 --> 00:04:03,680
One final issue I'd like to pinpoint is some students have the same name and

77
00:04:03,680 --> 00:04:08,120
age but different test scores like Amy Linn reported for the same test.

78
00:04:08,120 --> 00:04:10,685
We should only have one row for each student,

79
00:04:10,685 --> 00:04:13,230
which is a uniqueness issue.

